  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The AlterG®-anti-gravity treadmill provides lower body weight support which enables
      individuals to exercise without feeling their full body weight. How this body weight support
      influences cardiovascular, respiratory, vascular and metabolic parameters is currently
      unclear. Further, whether body weight support influences the trainability in response to
      moderate continuous exercise is unknown. This investigation has two main goals. First, we
      explore the direct influence of lower body weight support on cardiometabolic parameters
      during maximal exercise testing. Second, we aim to compare changes in cardiorespiratory
      fitness in response to a structured exercise protocol using moderate intensity with and
      without lower body weight support.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
